Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Boil a large #pot{} of @salt{for water}ed water for the potatoes.

Chop the @potatoes{2} into 2cm chunks (peeling optional).

Add the potatoes to the boiling water and cook until fork tender, ~{12-18%mins}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander{} and return to the pot, off the heat. Add a knob of @butter{1%knob} and a splash of @milk{1%splash}(optional) or @water{}. Mash with a #potato masher{} until smooth. Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic{1%clove} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}.

Place a large pan over medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste} and @butter{1%tbsp} (double for 4p).

When hot, fry the onion until softened, stirring occasionally, ~{4-5%mins}.

Meanwhile, remove the skin from the @haddock{250%g} and chop into 2cm chunks.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw fish.

Add @flour{2%tbsp} (double for 4p) to the pan. Cook until a paste forms, ~{1-2%mins}.

Stir in @water{150%ml} (double for 4p) and @vegetable stock{2%sachets} powder. Bring to the boil. Simmer, stirring, until thickened, ~{1-2%mins}.

Once thickened, stir through the @creme fraiche{65%g} along with the fish.

Simmer until the fish is cooked, ~{3-4%mins}.

> IMPORTANT: Fish is cooked when opaque in the middle.

Pour the contents of your pan into an appropriately-sized #oven dish{}.

Spread an even layer of mash over the creamy filling.

Sprinkle the @grated cheese{50%g} over the top.

Bake on the top shelf of your oven until golden, ~{12-15%mins}.

== Garlicky Peas ==

Meanwhile, place a small pot over medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Pop in the @garlic{1%clove}(grated) and @peas{120%g}.

Cook until warmed through, ~{3-5%mins}.

Season to taste with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

== To Serve ==

When everything is ready, divide the cheesy fish pie between #plates{}.

Serve with the garlicky green peas alongside.